🎧 About the Dataset — Toronto Emotional Speech Set (TESS)¶

The Toronto Emotional Speech Set (TESS) is a well-known emotional speech dataset developed to support research in affective computing and speech emotion recognition (SER).

📄 Dataset Structure¶

  • The dataset contains 2,800 audio recordings in total.
  • Recordings are based on 200 target words, each embedded in the carrier phrase:
    "Say the word '[target]'".
  • The words were spoken by two female actors:
    • One aged 26 years
    • One aged 64 years

Each phrase was spoken with seven distinct emotional intonations:

  • 😠 Anger
  • 🤢 Disgust
  • 😨 Fear
  • 😀 Happiness
  • 😮 Pleasant Surprise
  • 😢 Sadness
  • 😐 Neutral

# Path to the root dataset directory
tess_base_dir = './TESS Toronto emotional speech set data'

# Initialize containers
file_paths = []
file_emotions = []

# Define emotion mapping for known shorthand (if any appear like 'ps' -> surprise)
emotion_map = {
    'ps': 'surprise'
}

# Traverse subdirectories
for subfolder in os.listdir(tess_base_dir):
    subfolder_path = os.path.join(tess_base_dir, subfolder)
    
    if os.path.isdir(subfolder_path):
        for filename in os.listdir(subfolder_path):
            if filename.endswith('.wav'):
                # Example filename: YAF_back_angry.wav
                try:
                    emotion_code = filename.split('_')[2].lower().replace('.wav', '')
                    emotion = emotion_map.get(emotion_code, emotion_code)  # Map or use as-is
                    file_paths.append(os.path.join(subfolder_path, filename))
                    file_emotions.append(emotion)
                except IndexError:
                    print(f"Skipping file (unexpected format): {filename}")

# Convert to DataFrame
Tess_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Emotions': file_emotions,
    'Path': file_paths
})

📊 Waveplots and Spectrograms¶

🎵 Waveplots¶

Waveplots show how the amplitude (loudness) of an audio signal varies over time.
They help visualize the structure of speech or music — for example, where the audio gets louder, quieter, or silent.

  • X-axis: Time (in seconds)
  • Y-axis: Amplitude (signal intensity)
In [7]:
def waveplot(data, sr, emotion):
    """
    Display a waveplot for the given audio data.

    Parameters:
    - data (ndarray): Audio time series.
    - sr (int): Sampling rate.
    - emotion (str): Emotion label.
    """
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 4))
    librosa.display.waveshow(data, sr=sr, color='royalblue')
    plt.title(f'Waveform - Emotion: {emotion}', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')
    plt.xlabel('Time (s)', fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel('Amplitude', fontsize=12)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

🔊 Spectrograms¶

Spectrograms provide a time-frequency representation of audio.
They show how frequencies evolve over time and how much energy (volume) each frequency band carries at each moment.

  • X-axis: Time
  • Y-axis: Frequency (Hz or log scale)
  • Color Intensity: Amplitude in decibels (dB)

This makes them highly effective for tasks like emotion recognition, speech analysis, and sound classification.

In [8]:
def spectrogram(data, sr, emo):
    """
    Display a log-scaled spectrogram for the given audio data.
    
    Parameters:
    - data (ndarray): Audio time series.
    - sr (int): Sampling rate.
    - emo (str): Emotion label.
    """
    X = librosa.stft(data)
    Xdb = librosa.amplitude_to_db(np.abs(X))
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(14, 4))
    librosa.display.specshow(Xdb, sr=sr, x_axis='time', y_axis='log', cmap='magma')
    plt.colorbar(format='%+2.0f dB')
    plt.title(f'Spectrogram - Emotion: {emo}', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')
    plt.xlabel('Time (s)')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency (log Hz)')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

🎛️ Data Augmentation for Audio Emotion Recognition¶

Data augmentation involves generating new, slightly modified versions of existing samples to improve model generalization and reduce overfitting — especially useful when working with limited datasets.

🧠 Why Use Augmentation?¶

  • Improves model robustness
  • Reduces overfitting
  • Mimics real-world distortions
  • Creates data diversity from limited samples

🎧 Common Audio Augmentation Techniques¶

Technique Description
Noise Injection Adds small random noise to simulate real-world background environments.
Time Shifting Moves audio slightly forward/backward along the timeline.
Pitch Shifting Changes the frequency/pitch without altering speed.
Speed Tuning Slightly speeds up or slows down the audio.
Volume Control Randomly increases or decreases amplitude levels.
Time Stretching Alters duration without changing pitch.

🧪 Next Step¶

Let’s now apply and evaluate a few of these audio augmentation techniques on our dataset to see which improve model performance.

In [16]:
def add_noise(data, noise_factor=0.035):
    """Add Gaussian noise to the audio signal."""
    noise_amp = noise_factor * np.random.uniform() * np.amax(data)
    return data + noise_amp * np.random.normal(size=data.shape[0])

def time_stretch(data, rate=0.8):
    """Stretch the audio in time (rate <1 slows down, >1 speeds up)."""
    return librosa.effects.time_stretch(data, rate=rate)

def time_shift(data, shift_max=5):
    """Randomly shift the audio forwards or backwards."""
    shift_range = int(np.random.uniform(low=-shift_max, high=shift_max) * 1000)
    return np.roll(data, shift_range)

def pitch_shift(data, sr, n_steps=0.7):
    """Change the pitch of the audio (n_steps <0 lowers pitch, >0 raises pitch)."""
    return librosa.effects.pitch_shift(data, sr=sr, n_steps=n_steps)

🧠 Feature Extraction¶

In order to effectively train a machine learning model for Speech Emotion Recognition, it's crucial to convert raw audio signals into a compact, informative set of features. This project focuses on extracting the following five core audio features from each audio file:

🎯 Features Used:¶

  • Zero Crossing Rate
    Measures how frequently the audio signal crosses the zero amplitude axis. It helps in detecting noisiness or percussive elements.

  • Chroma Short-Time Fourier Transform (Chroma STFT)
    Represents the 12 different pitch classes (semitones of the musical octave), making it useful for capturing harmonic content.

  • MFCC (Mel-Frequency Cepstral Coefficients)
    Captures the timbral texture of audio based on how humans perceive sound frequencies. One of the most critical features for speech and music analysis.

  • RMS (Root Mean Square) Energy
    Provides a measure of the power (or loudness) of the signal over time. Helps capture energy fluctuations.

These features will be extracted using Librosa, a Python library specialized for music and audio analysis, and then used to train deep learning models for emotion classification.

In [20]:
def extract_features(data, sample_rate):
    """
    Extract essential audio features for Speech Emotion Recognition.

    Features included:
    1. Zero Crossing Rate (ZCR)
    2. Chroma STFT (12 chroma features)
    3. MFCC (13 coefficients)
    4. RMS Energy

    Parameters:
    - data (ndarray): Audio time series.
    - sample_rate (int): Sampling rate of the audio.

    Returns:
    - ndarray: A 1D array of combined extracted audio features.
    """
    result = []

    # 1. Zero Crossing Rate
    # Measures how often the signal crosses zero amplitude (useful for percussive sounds)
    zcr = librosa.feature.zero_crossing_rate(y=data)
    result.append(np.mean(zcr))

    # 2. Chroma STFT
    # Captures harmonic content across 12 pitch classes (like a musical octave)
    stft = np.abs(librosa.stft(data))
    chroma = librosa.feature.chroma_stft(S=stft, sr=sample_rate)
    result.extend(np.mean(chroma, axis=1))  # Add 12 chroma features

    # 3. MFCC (Mel-frequency cepstral coefficients)
    # Extract 13 MFCCs (standard for speech/audio tasks)
    mfcc = librosa.feature.mfcc(y=data, sr=sample_rate, n_mfcc=13)
    result.extend(np.mean(mfcc, axis=1))  # Add 13 MFCC features

    # 4. RMS Energy
    # Represents signal energy over time (related to loudness)
    rms = librosa.feature.rms(y=data)
    result.append(np.mean(rms))

    return np.array(result)  # Total features = 1 (ZCR) + 12 (Chroma) + 13 (MFCC) + 1 (RMS) = 27 features
In [24]:
def get_features(path):
    """
    Load audio data and extract features with and without augmentations.

    Augmentations:
    1. Noise Injection
    2. Time Stretching
    3. Time Shifting
    4. Pitch Shifting

    Parameters:
    - path (str): Path to the audio file.

    Returns:
    - ndarray: Combined features (original + augmented versions).
    """
    # Load audio with a fixed duration and offset to remove silence
    data, sample_rate = librosa.load(path, duration=2.5, offset=0.6)

    # Initialize with original audio features
    result = [extract_features(data, sample_rate)]

    # ➕ 1. Noise Injection
    noisy = add_noise(data)
    result.append(extract_features(noisy, sample_rate))

    # ➕ 2. Time Stretching (avoid extreme stretch for stability)
    stretched = time_stretch(data, rate=0.9)
    result.append(extract_features(stretched, sample_rate))

    # ➕ 3. Time Shifting
    shifted = time_shift(data)
    result.append(extract_features(shifted, sample_rate))

    # ➕ 4. Pitch Shifting
    pitched = pitch_shift(data, sample_rate)
    result.append(extract_features(pitched, sample_rate))

    # Combine all feature vectors into a single matrix
    return np.vstack(result)

📦 Feature Extraction & Dataset Creation¶

In this step, we extract features from each audio file in the TESS dataset using the previously defined get_features() function, which includes both the original signal and multiple augmented versions (noise, stretch, pitch, shift, etc.).

Each augmented version is treated as a separate training sample, but all inherit the same emotion label as the original file. This increases dataset diversity and improves model generalization.

🔄 Process Overview¶

  • Loop through every file in the dataset along with its corresponding emotion label.
  • Apply augmentation + feature extraction via get_features(path).
  • Store extracted feature vectors in X and their associated emotion labels in Y.

📊 Create and Save Dataset¶

  • A new Pandas DataFrame is constructed with extracted features.
  • The corresponding emotion label is stored in a labels column.
  • The final dataset is saved to a CSV file (features.csv) for future model training.

💡 Why Save as CSV?¶

Storing features in a CSV allows:

  • Faster training (no real-time feature extraction)
  • Easier reuse across multiple models or notebooks
  • Portable dataset format

Use RNN¶

In [38]:
# Define a function to create the RNN model
def create_rnn_model(input_shape, num_classes):
    # Initialize a sequential model
    model = Sequential()
    


    #  First RNN layer: 128 units
    # input_shape specifies the shape of the input data
    # return_sequences=True allows the next layer to receive the full sequence of outputs
    
    model.add(SimpleRNN(128, input_shape=input_shape, return_sequences=True)) 
    model.add(BatchNormalization()) # Normalize the outputs of the previous layer
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))# Apply dropout to prevent overfitting
    


    #  Second RNN layer: 64 units, returns full sequences
    model.add(SimpleRNN(64, return_sequences=True))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())  # Normalize outputs
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))          # Apply dropout


    
    # Third RNN layer: 32 units, returns final output
    model.add(SimpleRNN(32))        
    model.add(BatchNormalization())   # Normalize outputs


    
    # Output layer with 'num_classes' units for multi-class classification
    # Uses softmax activation function to output probabilities for each class
    model.add(Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax'))
    

    return model

Use LSTM model¶

In [47]:
def create_lstm_model(input_shape, num_classes):
    model = Sequential()

    # First LSTM layer
    model.add(LSTM(128, input_shape=input_shape, return_sequences=True))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))

    # Second LSTM layer
    model.add(LSTM(64, return_sequences=False))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))

    # Dense layer for learning combinations of extracted features
    model.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))

    # Output layer
    model.add(Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax'))

    return model

Predicting on test data¶

In [56]:
# Predicting on test data
# Use the trained model to generate predictions for the test dataset
pred_test = LSTM_model.predict(x_test)

# Convert probabilities to class labels
y_pred = np.argmax(pred_test, axis=1)

# Get the number of classes from the encoder
num_classes = encoder.categories_[0].size  # Number of classes based on the fitted encoder

# Convert predictions to one-hot encoding for inverse transformation
y_pred_one_hot = np.zeros((y_pred.size, num_classes))  # Use num_classes instead of encoder.n_classes_
y_pred_one_hot[np.arange(y_pred.size), y_pred] = 1

# Inverse transform the predicted labels back to their original form
y_pred_labels = encoder.inverse_transform(y_pred_one_hot)

# Inverse transform the true labels from y_test back to their original form
y_test_labels = np.argmax(y_test, axis=1)  # Convert one-hot encoded y_test back to class labels

# Convert true labels to one-hot encoding for inverse transformation
y_test_one_hot = np.zeros((y_test_labels.size, num_classes))
y_test_one_hot[np.arange(y_test_labels.size), y_test_labels] = 1
y_test_labels_original = encoder.inverse_transform(y_test_one_hot)

Create a DataFrame to store predicted and actual labels¶

In [57]:
# Create a DataFrame to store predicted and actual labels
df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Predicted Labels', 'Actual Labels'])

# Convert predicted labels to one-hot encoding before inverse transformation
predicted_one_hot = np.zeros((y_pred.size, encoder.categories_[0].size))
predicted_one_hot[np.arange(y_pred.size), y_pred] = 1

# Inverse transform the predicted labels to get the actual string labels
predicted_labels = encoder.inverse_transform(predicted_one_hot)

# Flatten the result to a 1D array
df['Predicted Labels'] = predicted_labels.flatten()

# Convert one-hot encoded y_test back to class labels if necessary
if len(y_test.shape) > 1:  # If y_test is one-hot encoded
    y_test_labels = np.argmax(y_test, axis=1)  # Get the class indices
else:
    y_test_labels = y_test.flatten()  # If already in the correct shape

# Create a one-hot encoded array for the actual labels
actual_one_hot = np.zeros((y_test_labels.size, encoder.categories_[0].size))
actual_one_hot[np.arange(y_test_labels.size), y_test_labels] = 1

# Inverse transform the actual labels to get the actual string labels
actual_labels = encoder.inverse_transform(actual_one_hot)

# Flatten the result to a 1D array
df['Actual Labels'] = actual_labels.flatten()

# Display the first 10 rows of the DataFrame to inspect the predicted and actual labels
df.sample(10)
